diff:1670117901:1670117901:=1,95d0%0a%3c (:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0a%3c Status: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!{$:Category}]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !Bahasa Rojak in Malaysia%0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: yeekitc%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Colloquial code-mixing in Malaysia's multilingual and multiethnic society%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Despite the systemic racial discrimination prevalent in Malaysia, which favors the predominant Muslim population, Malaysia is an incredibly multiethnic country. Apart from its two official languages English and Malay, two other languages (Tamil and Mandarin Chinese) and a multitude of other dialects (Hokkien, Cantonese, Jaffna Tamil and Tamil Nadu) are commonly heard. Amongst the indigenous people of Malaysia, Iban, Dusun, Kadazan, and more are also spoken. %0a%3c %0a%3c A large percentage of the Malaysian population is bilingual, if not trilingual. Thus, similar to many other multilingual societies, a phenomenon called code-mixing (single utterances contain more than one language) is present. “Bahasa Rojak”, or as literally translated from Malay, “mixed language”/”salad language”, is a byproduct of this fact. In the cultural melting pot of Malaysia, everyday conversation and slang tends to contain loanwords from all four of the main languages: English, Malay, Tamil, and Chinese. This is Bahasa Rojak. %0a%3c %0a%3c Despite its colloquial nature, some Malaysians take pride in Bahasa Rojak. It is a representation of the diversity within the country, and provides an umbrella that unites the ethnic groups. No matter the linguistic background of the person you are speaking to, chances are that they will understand slang in Bahasa Rojak. An example of this is the word for ordering takeout: “tapao”, or “tapau” is often used to opt to take out food rather than eating in.%0a%3c %0a%3c Malay is also referred to as “Bahasa Malaysia”, literally translated as “Malaysia Language”. In the eyes of many government officials, it is the mother tongue. However, since Bahasa Rojak borrows extensively from Malay, widespread usage of Bahasa Rojak can be a threat to fluency in Malay. Efforts to preserve the linguistic purity of the official languages and crack down on Bahasa Rojak have included fines for “incorrect” Malay signage, and educational reforms such as the contradictory ETeMS and MBMMBI (see Source 5). %0a%3c %0a%3c Sources: %0a%3c https://www.holidify.com/pages/languages-of-malaysia-3710.html %0a%3c https://omniglot.com/language/articles/bahasarojak.htm%0a%3c https://www.borneotalk.com/rojak-slangs-every-malaysian-should-know/ %0a%3c http://itre.cis.upenn.edu/~myl/languagelog/archives/003643.html %0a%3c https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/pdf/10.1177/1478210316679069 %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c You must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Commen